column2: %fuzzy set|Fuzzy sets% are characterized by membership (characteristic function) $f_A(x)$
%cf|$f_A(x)$% associates each point in %X|$X$% with a real number in the interval $[0,1]$
The value of %cf|$f_A(x)$% represents the "grade of membership" of $x$ in $A$
The nearer the vaue of %cf|$f_A(x)$% to unity, the higher the grade of membership of $x$ in %A|$A$%
Real number example of %fuzzy set|fuzzy sets%
Let %A|$A$% be a set of %fuzzy set|fuzzy numbers% which are much greater than 1
Some representative values of %rcf|$f_A(x)$% for the %r|real number example%
A %fuzzy set|fuzzy set% is empty if and only if its %cf|membership function% is identically zero on %X|$X$%
Two %fuzzy set|fuzzy sets% $A$ and $B$ are %equality|equal% if and only if %cf|$f_A(x)$%$ = $%cf|$f_B(x)$% for all $x$ in %X|$X$%
Notationally, %equality|equality% is written as %fuzzy set|$A$%$ = $%fuzzy set|$B$%
Notationally, we will write %cf|$f_A$% $=$ %cf|$f_B$% to represent %cf|$f_A(x)$%$ = $%cf|$f_B(x)$%
Despite some resemblence, there are essential differences between a probability function/a probability density function and the %cf|membership function% of a %fuzzy set|fuzzy set%
The %cf|membership function% has some resemblence to a probability function when %X|$X$% is a countable set
The %cf|membership function% has some resemblence to a probability density function when %X|$X$% is a continuum
The notion of a %fuzzy set|fuzzy set% is completely nonstatistical in nature
The notion of "belonging" does not have the same role in %fuzzy set|fuzzy sets% as it does in %ordinary set|ordinary sets%
The notion of "belonging" plays a fundamental role in the case of %ordinary set|ordinary sets%
It is generally not meaningful to speak of a point %X|$x$% "belonging" to a %fuzzy set|fuzzy set% A
In %ordinary set|ordinary sets%, the notion of "belonging" is meaningful in the trivial sense of %cf|$f_A(x)$% being positive
It is more meaningful to speak of a point %X|x% "belonging" to a %fuzzy set|fuzzy set% A when introducing thresholds to the %cf|characteristic function% output.
%fuzzy set|Fuzzy sets% provide a natural way of dealing with a class of problems which stem from imprecision
%fuzzy set|Fuzzy sets% are useful when source of imprecision is the absence of sharply defined criteria of %cf|class membership%
%fuzzy set|Fuzzy sets% are more general than %ordinary set|ordinary sets%
%fuzzy set|Fuzzy sets% may have a much wider scope of applicability than %ordinary set|ordinary sets%
%fuzzy set|Fuzzy sets% are particularly applicable in the field of pattern classification
%fuzzy set|Fuzzy sets% are particularly applicable in the field of information processing
A more intuitively appealing way of defining %union|union%
(less precise) The union of %A|A% and %A|B% is the smallest %fuzzy set|fuzzy set% %containment|containing% both %A|A% and %A|B%
(more precise) If %A|D% is any %fuzzy set|fuzzy set% which contains both %A|A% and %A|B%, then it also %containment|contains% the %union|union% of %A|A% and %A|B%
%alt cf union|This definition% is equivalent to the %cf union|alternative definition%
%intersection|Intersection% can be defined analogously to the %cf union|definition of union%
An %ordinary set|ordinary set% is a set with a two-valued characteristic function
Imprecision is sometimes caused by the absence of sharply defined criteria of %cf|class membership%
